          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>1 fol. on parchment; Shelfmark: E 16264 H; Qurʾānic Text: Q 40:52-40:70; Script style: kūfī B.II; Estimated date of production: 700-800 (?).</p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>This shelfmark entails four fragments from the same sheet. Fragment 1 has a size of around 168 x 84mm, fragment 2, 3 and 4 are contiguous and together have a size of 240 x 120mm. </p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>The catalogue of Arabic manuscripts kept by the University Museum in Philaldelphia, written by Giorgio Levi Della Vida gives the following information (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/78QP9SWH">Levi Della Vida 1981</ref>, p. 161):</p>
              <p>"131. Inv. E. 16264 H. 3rd-4th century A.H./9th-10th century A. D. Yellowish, thin parchment. Four fragments from the same sheet. <hi rend="italic">b</hi>, <hi rend="italic">c</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">d</hi> are contiguous; <hi rend="italic">a</hi> is seperated from them by a gap of ca. 2 cm. Dimensions of <hi rend="italic">a</hi>: 8.4 x 16.8 cm.: of <hi rend="italic">b</hi>+<hi rend="italic">c</hi>+<hi rend="italic">d</hi>: 12 x 24 cm. <hi rend="italic">a</hi> has preserved parts of the upper margin, 4 cm. wide, <hi rend="italic">c</hi> parts of the outer and lower margins, 3.7 and 2.4 cm. wide, and <hi rend="italic">d</hi>  parts of the inner margin. This sheet belongs to the same Koran copy as <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/1077"> no. 130 [E 16264 F]</ref>. From the Ellen W. Harrison Collection. <hi rend="italic">Recto a</hi>: Kor 40,52 (55) [معـ]ـذرتهم – 56 (58) [سـ]ـلطٰ[ـن];<hi rend="italic"> b+c+d</hi>: 40,57 (59) [ولكـ]ـن – 61 (63) الناس (first). <hi rend="italic">Verso </hi>a: 40,61 (63) اكثر – 64 (66) و[رزقكم]; <hi rend="italic">b+c+d</hi>: 40,66 (68) اللـه – 70 (72) كذبوا. Further features of the script which do not appear in no. 130 are: the <hi rend="italic">waṣl </hi>indicated by a red horizontal stroke across the <hi rend="italic">alif</hi>;  a gold rosette inscribed in a square as ten-verse divider, on recto  line 4 from the bottom, at the end of verse 59, which is 60 according to  the Damascus numbering (see<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/PWGCAS53"> A. Spitaler, <hi rend="italic">Die Verszählung des Koran</hi></ref>, p. 56: however our copy marks no verse end after البصير<hi rend="italic"> </hi>[sic!]<hi rend="italic"> </hi>in verse 58, as Damascus does)." </p>
            </summary>
